Define objectives of writeup

Among the articles listed on the Mashable site from January 7, 2013 to January 7, 2015 (2 years), 5947 articles are used for web mining. (However, as of January 7, 2015, articles from the last 3 weeks are not included. This is because it is judged that the number of shares is still insufficient.) We will use this data to predict the number of shares of articles.The original data has 63 variables, so we plan to perform regression analysis using PCA to reduce the dimensionality.

Data (Munging - EDA stage)

Data inport/gathering

online <- read.csv('OnlineNewsPopularity/OnlineNewsPopularity.csv')
data <- online

# -> categorical / channel 
channel_X <- c("lifestyle", "entertainment", "bus", "socmed", "tech", "world", "else")
channel_count <- c(table(online$data_channel_is_lifestyle)[2], table(online$data_channel_is_entertainment)[2], 
                   table(online$data_channel_is_bus)[2], table(online$data_channel_is_socmed)[2],
                   table(online$data_channel_is_tech)[2], table(online$data_channel_is_world)[2], 900)
channel_pct <- c(round((table(online$data_channel_is_lifestyle)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2), 
                 round((table(online$data_channel_is_entertainment)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2),
                 round((table(online$data_channel_is_bus)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2),
                 round((table(online$data_channel_is_socmed)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2),
                 round((table(online$data_channel_is_tech)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2),
                 round((table(online$data_channel_is_world)[2]/nrow(online))*100,2),
                 round((900/nrow(online))*100,2))
channel <- data.frame(channel_X, channel_count, channel_pct)
channel
{ ggplot(channel, aes(x = channel_X, y = channel_count, fill = channel_X)) +  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label=channel_pct), position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = 1.5, color = "black", size = 5) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = channel$channel_X) + 
  theme_gray(base_family = 'AppleGothic', base_size = 10)
}

transformations - center/scale - dummy variables

Based on the five continuous variables(LDA_00/01/02/03/04), a dummy variable, which is LDA_Topic, is created and it is a categorical variable. The variable of LDA_Topic is about the nearest LDA Topic that is related to LDA_00/01/02/03/04. Also, it show the visualization about the proportion of LDA Topic.

########################## dummy variable - LDA Topic ##########################
LDA_Topic <- c()
for (i in 1:nrow(online)) {
  LDA_Topic[i] <- which.max(online[i, c(40:44)])
}
online <- cbind(online, LDA_Topic)
online$LDA_Topic <- as.factor(online$LDA_Topic)

levels(online$LDA_Topic) <- c("Topic0","Topic1","Topic2","Topic3","Topic4")

tbl = table(online$LDA_Topic) 
tbl_cnt = data.frame(cbind(freq = tbl))
tbl_cnt$LDA_Topic = row.names(tbl_cnt)
row.names(tbl_cnt) = NULL
name <- names(table(online$LDA_Topic))
tbl = within(tbl_cnt, {pct = paste(round((freq / sum(freq))*100, 1), "%", sep="")})
tbl
{ ggplot(tbl, aes(x = LDA_Topic, y = freq, fill= LDA_Topic)) +  geom_bar(stat='identity') +
  geom_text(aes(label=pct), position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = 1.5, color = "black", size = 5) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = name) + 
  theme_gray(base_family = 'AppleGothic', base_size = 10) %+replace%
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 10, color = "black")) 
}

Now, lets talk about outliers. Since the variables of kw_min_min, kw_avg_min and kw_min_avg are related to the number of shares, they cannot be less than 0. However, if you check the table below, you can see that the minimum value is less than zero. Therefore, values less than 0 were replaced with 0. (kw_min_min: 22980, kw_avg_min: 833, kw_min_avg: 6)

Now, we check the variable of n_tokens_content regarding with the number of words in the content. If n_tokens_content is 0, it means that no text is written in the article. However, it is thought that the lack of words in the article is an error during the web mining process, so observations (1181) with n_tokens_content of 0 is removed. As shown below, it can be confirmed that the overall distribution does not change even if 1181 data items are removed from the original data.

Then, we remove the outliers of the response variable, shares variable. The value of shares ranges from 1 to 843300, and the histogram shows that the data becomes rarer as the shares values increases. Therefore, based on 7500, which is larger than 1.5 times of the IQR, shares variable with the value greater than 7500 are removed. If the standard is 1.5 times the IQR, there is too much data to be removed (4523 observations), and it was judged that it is more reasonable to cut the data based on 7500 through the histogram. This is a process for predicting data more accurately. The number of data larger than 7500 is 2995. This accounts for 7.79% of the total data. Also, we can see that there is no number smaller than the lower bound.

We consider the transformation of predictor and response variables. Some variables are skewed in one direction or their ranges of the values are larger than others. In this case, these variables should be transformed so that the data is spread evenly. Therefore, it is converted into root or log considering the characteristics of the variable. I will show the comparison of histogram before and after transformation.

################################ transformation #################################

Modeling

PCA is used to predict the number of shares, based on linear regression models. Because of the problem of too many variables, PCA is used in order to reduce the dimensionality of the data. However, applying with up to PC17 would explain 81% of the variance in this data. This isnt great, but its better than the original 45 variables. Therefore, regression analysis is performed by using this. In addition, since the number of variables is large, the number of variables is reduced by using stepwise regression among the variable selection methods. As a result of the regression analysis, the obtained results is not good, and box-cox transformation and weight least squared (WLS) are applied after confirming that the residuals have non-constant variance.

Evaluation - Discussion of what you saw/did

Validation is performed based on these three models. The train data and test data are divided 7 into 3 and proceeded 100 times to calculate AIC, BIC, and prediction accuracy, which is similar with mean of the error. As a result of this validation, I can figure out that the model with box-cox transformation has the smallest values of AIC, BIC, and prediction accuracy. It means that it is the best model among them. Nevertheless, it need to think of that the data is insufficient to predict the number of shares, and it is necessary to apply various models suitable for high-dimensional data.

set.seed(1234)
acc.result <- matrix(NA, 3, 100)
AIC.result <- matrix(NA, 3, 100)
BIC.result <- matrix(NA, 3, 100)

for (i in 1:100) {
  tt <- sample(nrow(pca.dat), round(nrow(pca.dat)*0.7, 0), replace=FALSE)
  train.set <- pca.dat[tt,]
  test.set <- pca.dat[-tt,]
  
  # model1.
  lm.fit <- lm(shares ~ PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC9 + 
                 PC10 + PC11 + PC12 + PC13 + PC14 + PC15 + PC17 + data_channel_is_entertainment + 
                 data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + 
                 data_channel_is_world + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + 
                 weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + 
                 LDA_Topic, data = train.set) 
  
  # model2. 
  resid <- residuals(lm.fit)
  absresid <- abs(resid)
  lmfitw0 <- lm(absresid ~ PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC9 + 
                  PC10 + PC11 + PC12 + PC13 + PC14 + PC15 + PC17 + data_channel_is_entertainment + 
                  data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + 
                  data_channel_is_world + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + 
                  weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + 
                  LDA_Topic, data = train.set)
  w <- 1/fitted(lmfitw0)^2
  wlm <- lm(shares ~ PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC9 + 
              PC10 + PC11 + PC12 + PC13 + PC14 + PC15 + PC17 + data_channel_is_entertainment + 
              data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + 
              data_channel_is_world + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + 
              weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + 
              LDA_Topic, weights = w, data = train.set)
  
  # Model3. Box-cox
  bc <- boxcox(lm.fit, plotit = FALSE, lambda = seq(-2, 2, by = 0.1))
  lam <- bc$x[which.max(bc$y)]
  if (lam == 0) {
    ytran <- log(train.set$shares)
  } else {
    ytran <- (train.set$shares^lam-1)/lam      
  } 
  boxcox.fit <- lm(ytran ~ PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC10 + 
                     PC12 + PC14 + PC15 + PC17 + data_channel_is_lifestyle + data_channel_is_entertainment + 
                     data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + 
                     data_channel_is_world + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + 
                     weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + 
                     LDA_Topic, data = train.set)
  
  acc.result[1, i] <- round(mean((test.set$shares - predict(lm.fit, test.set))^2), 4)
  acc.result[2, i] <- round(mean((test.set$shares - predict(wlm, test.set))^2), 4)
  if (lam == 0) {
    trans.pred <- exp(predict(boxcox.fit, test.set))
  } else {
    trans.pred <- (predict(boxcox.fit, test.set)*lam+1)^(1/lam)
  }
  acc.result[3, i] <- round(mean((test.set$shares - trans.pred)^2), 4)
  
  AIC.result[1, i] <-  AIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[1, 2]
  AIC.result[2, i] <-  AIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[2, 2]
  AIC.result[3, i] <-  AIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[3, 2]
  
  BIC.result[1, i] <-  BIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[1, 2]
  BIC.result[2, i] <-  BIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[2, 2]
  BIC.result[3, i] <-  BIC(lm.fit, wlm, boxcox.fit)[3, 2]
}

acc <- data.frame(t(acc.result))
par(mfcol = c(1, 1))
boxplot(acc, xlab = 'Model', ylab = "Prediction Accuracy", names=c("LM", "WLS", "Box-Cox"), main = 'Box-plot of prediction accuracy')

apply(acc.result, 1, mean)
